{
    "analysis": "From the last Executor results (provided summary), multiple of the five candidate services show metric, trace, and log anomalies during the incident window, with ts-auth-service and ts-order-service showing the strongest multi-signal anomalies (many KPIs each with anomalies_count_in_window = 2). log.error_count is zero for candidates and error_logs.csv is empty, so we must rely on metrics + traces to localize the root cause. According to the diagnosis rules, when multiple service-level faulty components are identified we should use traces to pick the most downstream faulty service in the call chain. The trace summaries already show anomalous trace groups for ts-auth-service and ts-order-service (e.g., trace.to_ts-auth-service.*, trace.from_root.*, trace.from_ts-order-service.*). To decide the root-cause service we need a compact, incident-window-focused trace analysis that: (1) computes per-trace-group anomalies using global P95 thresholds (calculated from the full series), (2) filters to the incident window, (3) extracts whether the trace refers to a call 'to' or 'from' a candidate service and the target service name, and (4) lists anomalous trace groups with earliest anomaly timestamps. This will let us identify traces where multiple candidate services are faulty and determine which candidate is the most downstream faulty service in the trace call chains. Next step: run a focused trace-group anomaly scan limited to the candidate services and the incident window, returning compact rows of anomalous trace groups sorted by earliest anomaly timestamp.\n",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "On trace.csv do the following: (1) parse timestamp as UTC datetimes (pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True)); (2) compute global P95 of 'value' for each trace group (group by cmdb_id and trace_name) using the full series; (3) filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 16:47:39 UTC to 2024-01-24 17:17:39 UTC; (4) restrict to trace groups where the cmdb_id is one of [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"] OR the trace_name references any of those services (trace_name contains 'ts-auth-service' or 'ts-order-service' or 'ts-route-service' or 'ts-train-service' or 'ts-travel-service'); (5) for each remaining (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute: global_p95 (from step 2), total_count_in_window, anomalies_count_in_window (count of rows in window where value > global_p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (UTC) or NA, latest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window or NA, max_value_in_window or NA; (6) also extract two helper fields from trace_name: direction (set to 'to' if trace_name contains 'to_ts-', 'from' if it contains 'from_ts-', 'root' if 'from_root' or 'to_root' appears, otherwise 'other') and referenced_service (if 'to_ts-XXX' or 'from_ts-XXX' present extract 'XXX', else NA); (7) return only rows with anomalies_count_in_window > 0, sorted by earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window ascending, limit 20 rows. Return a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, direction, referenced_service, global_p95, total_count_in_window, anomalies_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window, latest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window, max_value_in_window.",
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the preprocess and anomaly-detection steps: global thresholds were computed and incident-window anomalies were extracted. Metrics show multi-KPI anomalies on ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, and ts-route-service (typical anomalies_count_in_window = 2 per KPI). Trace aggregation (referenced-service view) shows the largest number of anomalous trace rows point to travel-service (70 anomalies) and order-service (51 anomalies), with many origins calling travel-service (including ts-order-service and ts-route-service). Logs show elevated log.row_count but log.error_count is zero and error_logs.csv is empty. According to the rules, when multiple service-level components are faulty we must pick the most downstream faulty service in trace call chains. The referenced-service trace summary indicates travel-service is the most frequent downstream target of anomalous traces and is called by other faulty services (order, route, etc.), which suggests ts-travel-service is the likely downstream root cause. However, to be confident we need metric-based fault identification severity per candidate: quantify for each candidate service which KPIs are anomalous in the incident window, the earliest anomaly timestamp per KPI, and a severity measure (how far max_value exceeds global_p95). This will let us (a) confirm which candidate services truly exhibited faults (not just callers), and (b) measure whether ts-travel-service shows strong metric deviations or is only implicated by traces. Next step: compute per-component-KPI anomaly summaries and per-component aggregated severity for the five candidate services to confirm the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the candidate services [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"] on metric.csv do the following: (1) parse timestamp as UTC datetimes (pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True)); (2) for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute the global P95 of 'value' using the full series (do NOT filter by window when computing P95); (3) filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 16:47:39 UTC to 2024-01-24 17:17:39 UTC; (4) mark rows as anomalous if value > global_p95 for their group; (5) aggregate per (component, kpi_name) and produce these fields: component, kpi_name, global_p95, anomalies_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (UTC) or NA, max_value_in_window or NA, severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / global_p95 (or NA if global_p95==0); (6) also produce a per-component summary: component, total_anomalies_across_kpis, earliest_anomaly_overall, max_severity_ratio_overall. Return: (A) per-KPI rows with anomalies_count_in_window>0 sorted by severity_ratio desc then anomalies_count desc, limit 20 rows; (B) the per-component summary for the five services. If a component has no rows in the window, include it in the per-component summary with total_anomalies_across_kpis=0 and other fields NA."
}

